## Service accounts

Service accounts (SAs) are **not exempt from permissions**. They participate in the permission system like any other actor:

- An SA has its own personal access group ID (derived from its SA ID).
- `runAsServiceAccount` sets the SA's scope permissions and access IDs on the request-scoped `MemStorage`, exactly as the user middleware does for human users.
- SA must be included in the relevant `__access` lists of documents it needs to interact with — the document access guards apply to SAs just as they apply to users.
- The only exception is **document creation** — during creation, `__access` is being stamped (not checked), so the SA can create documents and define their access actors.

```typescript
import {ModuleBE_Permissions, ServiceAccountId_Bootstrap} from '@nu-art/permissions-backend';

await ModuleBE_Permissions.runAsServiceAccount(ServiceAccountId_Bootstrap, async () => {
	await ModuleBE_AccessGroupDB.set.all([...]);
});
```

Service accounts are defined in module config:

```typescript
type ServiceAccountConfig = {
	readonly scopes: string[];      // scope entries like ['permissions:admin']
	readonly enabled: boolean;
	readonly systemOnly: boolean;   // if true, cannot be used within a user request context
};
```

The `bootstrap-admin` SA is registered by default. Its scope entries are dynamically resolved to the highest value of every registered scope.

**Do not bypass permissions in any other way.** No flags, no middleware skipping, no direct MemKey manipulation. `runAsServiceAccount` is the only elevation mechanism.

