## Naming conventions

| Artifact | Convention |
|----------|-----------|
| Scope constant | `PermissionScope_<Domain>` |
| Scope definition file | `permission-scope.ts` in the concept's shared package |
| Scope entity IDs | `permissionScopeId(key, value)` — deterministic via md5, do not wrap |
| Group definition constant | `AccessGroup_<Name>` |
| Group IDs | `hashToUniqueId<DatabaseDef_AccessGroup["dbKey"]>('group/<key>')` |
| Service account IDs | `ServiceAccountId_<Name>` string constants |

---

## Forbidden patterns

- **Never use the old domain/access-level model** (`PermissionDomain`, `PermissionAccessLevel`, `CollectPermissionsProjects`). Legacy infrastructure — do not use in application code.
- **Never define scopes in backend-only packages.** Both FE and BE must access the scope registry.
- **Never create trivial ID wrapper functions.** Use `stringToUniqueId<DatabaseDef_*["dbKey"]>(id)` directly at the call site.
- **Never bypass permissions** with flags, env vars, or direct MemKey writes. `runAsServiceAccount` is the only elevation mechanism, and even it participates in the permission system — it does not bypass document access.
- **Never modify system groups** from app-level code. They are bootstrap-only.
- **Never create a document without correct `__access` actors.** Once created, the permission guards apply. A document with wrong or missing access actors will be inaccessible.
- **Every DB collection is automatically permission-gated** via `wireDocumentAccess` on all modules. Set an `AccessContextResolver` for modules that need custom access resolution.

